07004nam a22009615i 9783111048789DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831110487897 a10.1515/97831110487892doi  a(DE-B1597)637963  a(OCoLC)1393307479  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04aThe Digital (R)Evolution of Legal Discourse :bNew Genres, Media, and Linguistic Practices /ced. by Patrizia Anesa, Jan Engberg. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IV, 160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFoundations in Language and Law [FLL] ,x2627-3950 ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tInvestigating legal discourse in the digital landscape -- tContract macrodivisions and the digital age -- tProcessing of personal data in Court Proceedings: A model for linguistic and legal studies -- tLegal specialists telling their stories on the internet: A comparative analysis of professional self-portrayals on German and Italian law firm websites -- tStance features in legal blogging -- tThe Internet as a game changer in legal communication: Arbitration on the move -- tLinguistic markers of participation in international criminal trials -- tMaking national immigration and asylum case law accessible to a non-Italian audience: The role of intra-lingual translation -- tScreening the law: Popularization practices in “How To Get Away With Murder” -- tAbout the authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe primary goal of this book is to reach a better understanding of how the digital revolution has affected language and discourse practices in the field of law. It also explores the complex nature of the techniques and discursive strategies which emerge in the relationship between the different stakeholders (including non-experts) thanks to technological advances. By adopting a discourse analytical perspective which combines both qualitative and quantitative approaches, the book explores the hybridity of new genres and communicative processes. It provides an interdisciplinary platform for researchers, practitioners, and educators to present the most recent innovations, trends, and concerns, as well as any solutions already adopted in their professional areas. Their insights converge in a truly multidisciplinary effort to devise and build advanced networks of knowledge to facilitate the interpretation of data in the field of legal linguistics - with a specific focus on digitalisation processes which concern contemporary legal discourse. The book is meant for scholars interested in the evolution of the interconnection between language and law in digital environments. It also addresses law and linguistics students, ideally with some training in language analysis and particular interest in new media and genres. All necessary linguistic or legal technicalities are, however, approached while bearing in mind a wide range of potential backgrounds and levels of education.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aDigitale Kommunikation. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aGenreanalyse. 4aRechtslinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aDigital Communication.  aDiscourse Analysis.  aGenre Analysis.  aLegilinguistics.1 aAnesa, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnesa, Patrizia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuniatova, Farida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemenzi, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiani, Giuliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela